HAND, FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - USA: (ARKANSAS)
**********************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 16 May 2011
Source: 4029tv.com [edited]
http://www.4029tv.com/news/27918437/detail.html


Hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) can easily be prevented by just
washing your hands, and doctors [in Fort Smith , Arkansas] said
they've been seeing more cases this season. "It's easily spread in
younger children, preschool children, school-aged children, and in day
cares. We're seeing an increase in the area currently," Ranata
Hatcher, a pediatric nurse practitioner, said.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said the illness
usually starts after a fever, then rashes can appear on arms and legs,
even ulcers can appear in your child's mouth, causing him or her pain
when eating or drinking foods. Hatcher said, "It's spread through
saliva, eating, and drinking after each other. That's why it's so
prevalent in preschools and day cares."

And preventing it is as easy as cleaning toys with bleach and washing
your hands. "We recommend you rub your hands together, cleaning under
your fingernails, between your fingers, backs of the hands. If you
teach them the ABC's while they're washing their hands, that's about
the time frame you need to efficiently kill all the germs," Hatcher
said.

Parents shouldn't be afraid; the disease has nothing to do with
animals. "HFMD is specific to humans. Foot-and-mouth disease is
something that you see in animals, you cannot catch hand-foot-mouth
disease from an animal," Hatcher said.

Hatcher said not being clean is the no. 1 cause for the spread of
hand- foot-mouth disease. If your child is showing signs of
dehydration, a symptom of the illness, you might want to call your
doctor.

[Byline: Tony Russell]

