[HFMD is caused by viruses that belong to the genus _Enterovirus_.
This genus of viruses includes the polioviruses, coxsackieviruses,
echoviruses, and enteroviruses. Coxsackievirus A16 has been the most
common cause of HFMD in the United States in recent years, but other
coxsackieviruses have been associated with the illness. Other
enteroviruses, such as enterovirus 71, have also been associated with
outbreaks of HFMD, principally in Asia.

Individual cases and outbreaks of HFMD occur worldwide. In temperate
climates cases occur more often in summer and early autumn. HFMD
caused by coxsackievirus A16 infection is generally a mild disease,
with nearly all patients recovering in 7 to 10 days without medical
treatment. Since 1997, however, outbreaks of HFMD caused by
enterovirus 71 have been reported in Asia and Australia. HFMD caused
by enterovirus 71 has shown a higher incidence of neurologic
involvement and fatal cases of encephalitis have occurred during
outbreaks. However, such serious outcomes are still very rare.

HFMD infection is spread from person to person by direct contact.
Infectious virus is found in the nose and throat secretions, saliva,
blister fluid and stool of infected persons. The virus is most often
spread by persons with unwashed, virus-contaminated hands and by
contact with virus-contaminated surfaces. Infected persons are most
contagious during the 1st week of the illness, but may remain a source
of infection for others after symptoms have resolved.

Complications from virus infections that cause HFMD are uncommon;
"aseptic" meningitis can occur rarely with HFMD causing fever,
headache, stiff neck, or back pain. Some patients may require
hospitalization for a short time. Other more serious conditions, such
as encephalitis, are very rare although encephalitis can be fatal.
There have been reports of fingernail and toenail loss occurring
mostly in children within 4 weeks of having HFMD (see: ProMED-mail
postings Onychomadesis, coxsackievirus - USA: (MI), RFI 20080729.2317;
Onychomadesis - Spain: (Valencia), coxsackievirus 20080709.2099; and
Onychomadesis - Spain: (Valencia), coxsackievirus (02) 20080711.2120).
At this time, it is not known whether the reported nail loss is or is
not a result of the infection. However, nail loss has been temporary
and nail growth has resumed without medical treatment.

Further information about HFMD can be obtained from the CDC website
at http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/revb/enterovirus/hfhf.htm.

It is difficult to assess the seriousness of the outbreak of HFMD at
Fort Smith in the absence of information on the number of children
(and adults) affected and without identification of the causative
agent. - Mod.CP]

[Fort Smith can be located via the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive
map at http://healthmap.org/r/0Rit. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
